  "prompt": "Can I use Google images in my website?",
  "response": "Using images directly from Google Images on your website without proper permission is generally not recommended, as it may infringe on copyright laws. Google Images is a search tool that indexes images from various sources across the web, but these images are typically owned by the original creators or publishers who may have specific restrictions on their use.\n\nIf you want to use images on your website, consider the following options:\n\n1. **Creative Commons Licenses**: Look for images that are licensed under Creative Commons. Websites like Flickr and Wikimedia Commons often have such images, but always make sure to check the specific license terms and comply with them.\n\n2. **Stock Photo Websites**: Consider using stock photo websites like Unsplash, Pexels, or Pixabay, which offer high-quality images that can often be used for free (with or without attribution, depending on the terms).\n\n3. **Purchase Licenses**: Use paid stock image services like Shutterstock, Adobe Stock, or Getty Images, where you can purchase licenses to use images legally.\n\n4. **Create Your Own Images**: If possible, take your own photos or create graphics tailored to your website's needs. This ensures originality and avoids any copyright issues.\n\n5. **Obtain Permission**: If you find a specific image you want to use, contact the owner or creator to ask for permission. They may grant you the rights to use the image under specific conditions.\n\nAlways ensure you have the right to use an image and provide any needed attribution if required by the license, to respect the intellectual property rights of the creators.",
